    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>What Dagger?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kirk Saduski letter on Michele Willens' June 25 article holds that if William Shakespeare had benefit of testing his plays before handpicked audience, Romeo and Juliet would have lived happily ever after (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Imagine if William Shakespeare had the benefit of testing his plays before a handpicked audience [''Putting Films to the Test, Every Time,'' by Michele Willens, June 25]. Undoubtedly, Romeo and Juliet would have lived happily ever after.</p>
        <p>KIRK SADUSKI  Santa Monica, Calif.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Imagine if William Shakespeare had the benefit of testing his plays before a handpicked audience [''Putting Films to the Test, Every Time,'' by Michele Willens, June 25]. Undoubtedly, Romeo and Juliet would have lived happily ever after.</p>
        <p>KIRK SADUSKI  Santa Monica, Calif.</p>
        <p>TEST SCREENINGS</p>
      </block>
